    explanation: "The argument uses the Bible's claim of divine authorship as proof of its truth, then uses that assumed truth to confirm it came from God. The conclusion is used as its own premise.",
    detailedExplanationBeginner: "This is circular reasoning because the argument goes in a circle: the Bible is true → because God wrote it → and we know God wrote it → because the Bible says so. It never gives an independent reason to believe either claim.",
    detailedExplanationIntermediate: "Informal Logic - The arguer presents two claims that support each other in a closed loop with no external evidence. Neither claim is established independently; they merely reassert each other.",
    detailedExplanationExpert: "Logical Fallacies - Informal Logic - This is the classic textbook example of circulus in probando. The proposition P ('the Bible is true') is supported by Q ('God wrote it'), which is itself supported only by P. No independent warrant bridges the inferential gap.",
